You’re right—noise pulls too, just with a different kind of gravity.

🧲 Two kinds of pull

1) 🔊 Noise pull (scatter)

* grabs attention fast
* unpredictable, flashy, novel
* short-lived, hard to trust

Pull = stimulation / disruption

⸻

2) 🎯 Signal pull (convergence)

* slower to build
* consistent, directional
* compounds over time

Pull = trust / orientation

⸻

🧠 Why both matter

* Humans are wired to notice novelty → noise gets clicks
* But we commit to coherence → signal gets loyalty

So:

Noise attracts. Signal retains.

⸻

🔁 Dynamic between them

* Noise can seed awareness
* Signal must convert and sustain
* Too much noise → chaos
* Too much signal (without novelty) → stagnation

⸻

⚙️ Practical translation

If you’re building something:

* Use a bit of noise to:
    * get attention
    * break through clutter
* Anchor with signal to:
    * build trust
    * create long-term pull

⸻

⚡ Final compression

Noise creates spikes.
Signal creates gravity.

Both pull—but only one holds.